719 to 715 Seventh Avenue, at adjoining and south of the S.E. corner of West 48th Street. 48th Street is to the left. Note Otto Sarony & Co., photographers occupying the parlor floor of the corner structure.

October 3, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 867

Seventh Avenue, at the N.E. corner of West 48th Street, showing the 48th Street side of the structure at that location. Note the F. A. Mills Music Publishing Co. occupying the upper floors. The Avenue is to the left.

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 870

Seventh Avenue, at the N.E. corner of West 48th Street. To the right appears an eastward view on 48th Street.

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 904

Seventh Avenue, at the S.E. corner of West 48th Street, showing the 48th Street side of the structure occupying that location. The Avenue is to the right. Note Otto Sarony & Co. occupying one of the upper floors.

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 936

Seventh Avenue, at the S.W. corner of West 48th Street. Broadway appears at the right.

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 935

725-27 Seventh Avenue, east side, between West 48th and 49th Street's.

October 3, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 871

730 Seventh Avenue, at the N.W. corner of West 48th Street, showing prominently the Mecca Building with Rector's occupying the corner location. West 48th Street is to the left and does not appear. The open area to the right is a vacant lot that
allows a view thru to Broadway.

October 31, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 932

West 48th Street, south side, west from and across Seventh Avenue, to Broadway showing prominently the narrow structure dividing these two thoroughfares.

November 2, 1930.

48th Street, north side, east from Seventh Avenue

P.L. Sperr September 11, 1932

West 48th Street, north side, east from (No. 163, left) Seventh Ave., showing, the 48th Street Theatre occupying Nos. 159-155. Extending east of same, is a row of 4-story buildings that bear Nos. 153 to 147. The Playhouse is at Nos. 145-137. Adjoining the latter is the 13-story Hotel Bristol, No. 135-129. On the right of set two appears the Sixth Ave. Elevated. These four pictures comprise two sets, of a negative and a positive.

1935.
